1 SECTION 3.1.(a) Article 56A of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by
2 adding a new section to read:
3 "§ 58-56A.22. Reporting requirements for transparency.
4 (a) Reports to Commissioner. – No later than May 1 of every year, all pharmacy benefits
5 managers shall report to the Commissioner all of the following information regarding
6 prescription drug benefits specific to insurers within the State with which a pharmacy benefits
7 manager has a contract:
8 (1) The aggregate amount of the rebates that the pharmacy benefits manager
9 received from all drug manufacturers or whole distributers by therapeutic
10 category of prescription drugs. In reporting the aggregate amount of the
11 rebates, the pharmacy benefits manager shall include any utilization discounts
12 it receives from a manufacturer or wholesale distributor.
13 (2) The aggregated amount of difference between the amount paid by the health
14 benefit plan for prescription drugs and the aggregated amount paid to
15 pharmacies for claims paid under the health benefit plan, including
16 point-of-sale and retroactive charges.
17 (3) The spread between aggregate amount paid to pharmacies for prescription
18 drugs and the aggregated amount charged to insurers for prescription drugs.
19 (4) A list of all pharmacies that are under common control or ownership of the
20 pharmacy benefits manager.
21 (5) A pharmacy benefits manager that is affiliated with a retail pharmacy shall
22 provide the aggregated amount of any differences between what the pharmacy
23 benefits manager reimburses or charges affiliated retail pharmacies and what
24 it reimburses or charges non-affiliated retail pharmacies.
25 (6) The aggregate amount of all fees or other assessments, including point-of-sale
26 and retroactive charges, that are imposed on, or collected from, contracted,
27 preferred, or in-network pharmacies. Retroactive charges shall not include any
28 funds recouped from an audit conducted under Part 8 of Article 50 of Chapter
29 58 of the General Statutes.
30 (7) The aggregate amount of rebates and fees that were passed on to either the
31 insurer with which the pharmacy benefits manager is contracted or an insured
32 at the point-of-sale of a prescription drug.
33 (8) The highest, lowest, and mean aggregate percentages for retained rebates by
34 the pharmacy benefits manager.
35 (b) Reports to Insurers. – Upon the request of an insurer with which a pharmacy benefits
36 manager is contracted, the pharmacy benefits manager shall prepare an annual report that
37 discloses the total amount of the difference between the amount paid by each contracted health
38 benefit plan offered by the insurer for prescription drugs and the aggregated amount paid to
39 pharmacies for claims paid under each applicable health benefit plan.
40 (c) Confidentiality of Data. – Information contained in a report required under this
41 section shall not reveal any personally identifiable information of any insured. Information
42 contained in this report is not considered a public record under Chapter 132 of the General
43 Statutes or under G.S. 58-2-100 and is confidential and privileged."
44 SECTION 3.2.(a) G.S. 58-56A-4 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
45 "(g) No pharmacy benefits manager contract may require, either directly or indirectly or
46 through a pharmacy services administration organization, an independent pharmacy to accept
47 reimbursement for providing a covered prescription drug, device, or service at a rate less than the
48 acquisition cost for the covered drug, device, or service. A violation of this section is an unfair
49 trade practice under Article 63 of this Chapter and under G.S. 75-1.1 and is subject to all of the
50 enforcement and penalty provisions of an unfair trade practice under this Chapter and under
51 Article 1 of Chapter 75 of the General Statutes."
