15 PART IX. PRESCRIPTION DRUG TRANSPARENCY
16 SECTION 9.(a) Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
17 Article to read:
18 "Article 4D.
19 "Prescription Drug Transparency.
20 "§ 90-85.55. Definitions.
21 The following definitions apply in this Article:
22 (1) Interested parties. – All of the following:
23 a. State agencies that (i) purchase prescription drugs or (ii) employ
24 prescribers.
25 b. Health insurance companies.
26 c. Health care service plan providers.
27 d. Pharmacy benefits managers.
28 (2) Manufacturer. – An entity or an agent of an entity that produces, prepares,
29 propagates, compounds, processes, packages, repackages, or labels a
30 brand-name or generic drug. "Manufacturer" does not include an entity
31 engaged in the preparation and dispensing of a brand-name or generic drug
32 pursuant to a prescription.
33 (3) Prescriber. – Any person authorized under the laws of this State to issue a
34 prescription order.
35 (4) Prescription drug. – Defined in G.S. 90-85.3.
36 (5) Prescription order. – Defined in G.S. 90-85.3.
37 (6) Price. – The wholesale acquisition cost as defined in 42 U.S.C. §
38 1395w-3a(c)(6)(B).
39 (7) Secretary. – The Secretary of the Department of Health and Human Services.
40 "§ 90-85.56. Required notifications and disclosures.
41 (a) Price Increases. – By January 31 of each year, a manufacturer shall notify all
42 interested parties of each increase in price of fifteen percent (15%) or greater that occurred in the
43 prior calendar year for a prescription drug with a price of one hundred dollars ($100.00) or more
44 for a 30-day supply. The manufacturer shall disclose all of the following to interested parties for
45 each drug price increase noticed for the prior calendar year under this subsection:
46 (1) The date and price of acquisition of the drug, if it was not developed by the
47 manufacturer.
48 (2) A schedule of price increases for the drug for the five years prior to the
49 calendar year for which the drug price increase was required to be noticed
50 under this subsection.
Senate Bill 479-Second Edition Page 17

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) New Products. – A manufacturer shall notify all interested parties of the price of any
2 new prescription drug within three days after it is made available for purchase in this State.
3 Within 30 days after the notification required by this subsection, the manufacturer shall disclose
4 to interested parties the date and price of acquisition of the drug if it was not developed by the
5 manufacturer.
6 (c) Satisfaction of Obligations. – A manufacturer's obligations under this section shall be
7 fully satisfied by the submission of information and data that a manufacturer includes in its
8 annual consolidated report on Securities and Exchange Commission Form 10-K or any other
9 public disclosure.
10 (d) Information is Not Public Record. – Information provided to the Secretary or an
11 interested party pursuant to this section shall, except to the extent it is already in the public
12 domain, be considered trade secret under Article 24 of Chapter 66 of the General Statutes,
13 confidential, exempt from public inspection and copying under Chapter 132 of the General
14 Statutes, and shall not be disclosed directly or indirectly. The Secretary, interested parties, and
15 their agents shall not publish or otherwise disclose any information that would allow for the
16 identification of an individual drug, therapeutic class of drugs, or manufacturer, that would reveal
17 the prices of any drug or therapeutic class of drugs, or that has the potential to compromise the
18 financial, competitive, or proprietary nature of any information submitted by the manufacturer
19 pursuant to this section. The Secretary and interested parties shall impose the confidentiality
20 protections of this section on any downstream third party that may receive or otherwise have
21 access to this information.
22 "§ 90-85.57. Penalty for failure to report.
23 The Secretary shall assess a civil penalty against any manufacturer failing to report the
24 information required by this Article. The amount of the penalty shall not exceed one thousand
25 dollars ($1,000) for each day the manufacturer fails to submit the required information. The clear
26 proceeds of any civil penalties assessed pursuant to this section shall be remitted to the Civil
27 Penalty and Forfeiture Fund in accordance with G.S. 115C-457.2. Chapter 150B of the General
28 Statutes applies to proceedings for the assessment of civil penalties under this section.
29 "§ 90-85.58. Report and data collection by the Secretary; public portal.
30 (a) Plan for Implementation. – The Secretary shall develop a plan to collect data from
31 manufacturers pursuant to G.S. 90-85.56 to provide transparency and accountability for
32 prescription drug pricing. The Secretary shall consult with other state and national agencies and
33 nonprofit organizations to determine how to implement this data collection directive but shall not
34 disclose any confidential, proprietary, or trade secret information.
35 (b) Public Portal. – The Secretary shall create an online portal to provide the public with
36 access to the notifications, reports, and other disclosures required by this Article.
37 (c) Annual Report. – Beginning March 1, 2026, and annually thereafter, the Secretary
38 shall report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services the
39 following information with respect to prescription drugs sold in this State:
40 (1) The 25 drugs prescribed most frequently in the State.
41 (2) The 25 most costly drugs based on the total amount spent on those drugs by
42 consumers in this State.
43 (3) The 25 drugs with the greatest percentage cost increases during the prior
44 calendar year.
45 (4) The 10 manufacturers with the greatest average percentage cost increase for
46 the prior calendar year for all drugs sold by that manufacturer in the State."
47 SECTION 9.(b) This Part is effective when it becomes law.
48
49 PART X. PHARMACY REPORTING REQUIREMENTS
50 SECTION 10. Article 4A of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by
51 adding a new section to read:
Page 18 Senate Bill 479-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 90-85.42. Board of Pharmacy reporting.
2 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
3 (1) Chain pharmacy. – Four or more pharmacies under a common ownership.
4 (2) Independent pharmacy. – Three or fewer pharmacies under a common
5 ownership.
6 (b) Reporting Requirements. – No later than October 1 of each year, the Board shall
7 report the following information to the Department of Insurance and the Joint Legislative
8 Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services:
9 (1) The current number of licensed pharmacies in the State.
10 (2) The number of independent pharmacies that have opened in the preceding five
11 years.
12 (3) The number of chain pharmacies that have opened in the preceding five years.
13 (4) The number of independent pharmacies that have closed in the preceding five
14 years.
15 (5) The number of chain pharmacies that have closed in the preceding five years."
16
17 PART XI. EFFECTIVE DATE
18 SECTION 11.1. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
19 law.
